Modeling gold — the patterns business intelligence and machine learning want.

Two patterns cover most gold tables.

The first is the star schema — facts surrounded by conformed dimensions. The bank's analytical reports run on a fact table of card transactions, with foreign keys out to dimensions like customer, merchant, and date. Those dimensions usually change slowly. When a customer's city changes, slowly-changing-dimension type two captures the change while preserving the history — and apply-changes-into stored-as scd type two is exactly the right tool for that.

The second is the wide rollup, sometimes called one big table. That's one row per business entity with every interesting metric inline — the customer three-sixty, with the customer id and thirty-odd rollup columns. It's easier for analysts to query because there are no joins, but it's more expensive to refresh.

So choose by consumer. Business-intelligence dashboards in tools like power bi or tableau want a star schema. Ad-hoc analytics teams and machine-learning feature engineering tend to want the one-big-table shape.
